==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*bīda-'', from Indo-European ''*bheidh-''.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Saxon [[bidan#Old Saxon|bīdan]], Old High German [[bitan|bītan]], Old Norse [[bíða]] (Swedish [[bida]]), Gothic [[𐌱𐌴𐌹𐌳𐌰𐌽]]

''Indo-European cognates:'' Greek [[πείθω]], Latin [[fidere]], Slavic ''*-bīdītī'' (Old Church Slavonic [[бѣждѫ]], Russian [[бедить]]), Albanian [[bint]]

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'bi:dan/

===Verb===
{{Unicode|'''bīdan'''}} (class I strong)
# to [[wait]], to wait for
#:''He geþyldum bad'': he waited patiently.
# to [[stay]], to [[remain]]
#:''Mere stille bad'': the sea remained calm.

